Introduction¶

Prosper is America's first peer-to-peer lending marketplace and was founded in 2005. Prosper connects borrowers with willing investors, and takes a small fee. Peer-to-peer lending often attracts borrowers who are unable to qualify for traditional bank loans.

I conducted an Explanatory Data Analysis (EDA) on the loan data set obtained from Propser. The data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The data set covers the time period 2005 to 2014, the first 9 years of the business.

Quality Issues¶

  • Missing data in ProsperRating (Alpha),ProsperScore, BorrowerAPR, Occupation, DebtToIncomeRatio, BorrowerState
  • Erroneous Datatype (ListingCreationDate in string instead of datetime format)
  • Non-descriptive values, datatype, and column name for ListingCategory (numeric)

Tidiness Issue¶

  • Date and Time stamp in ListingCreationDate not suitable for analysis

Cleaning Data¶

Issue #1:¶
  • Missing data in ProsperRating (Alpha),ProsperScore, BorrowerAPR, Occupation, DebtToIncomeRatio, BorrowerState
Define¶

For this analysis, ProsperRating is a very important variable as it is a rating assigned to each Borrower Loan at the time it is posted for bids on the prosper platform. This rating is calculated using a number of elements, especially the ProsperScore, and Credit Score from the consumer credit bureau.

Loan Listings also include the Prosper Rating, which is a letter grade that indicates the level of risk associated with the listing. Hence, for this analysis, we cannot have null values in the ProsperRating column.

Due to the missing ProsperRating values, data cleaning will start with the following steps:

  • Change column name from ProsperRating (Alpha) to ProsperRating
  • Select non-null values in the ProsperRating column
  • Drop the remaining null values in ProsperScore and BorrowerState columns
  • fill missing values in DebtToIncomeRatio with the mean
  • fill missing values in Occupation with "Unknown"
Code¶

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Structure of dataset¶

The cleaned data set contains 84,853 loans with 16 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Main feature(s) of interest in dataset¶

In this analysis, the main variables of interest are Loan Status and interest rate

I am most interested in exploring:

  • What factors affect the borrower's interest rates
  • The relationships among multiple variables using summary statistics and data visualizations

Features in the dataset to support the investigation into the main feature(s) of interest¶

There are a lot of variables to explore, but for this analysis, my focus will mainly be on 13 variables from the original data set and the 2 newly created variables (listing_year, listing_month):

  • ListingKey - Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.
  • Listing_year - The year the listing was created.
  • Listing_month - The month the listing was created.
  • LoanStatus - The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  • Term - The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • ProsperScore - A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-11, with 11 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • ProsperRating - Prosper Ratings allow investors to consider a loan's level of risk because the rating represents an estimated average annualized loss rate range. The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR, with AA being the best, or lowest risk rating. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • BorrowerRate - The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • ListingCategory - The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: (Not Available, Debt Consolidation, Home Improvement, Business, Personal Loan, Student Use, Auto, Other, Baby&Adoption, Boat, Cosmetic Procedure, Engagement Ring, Green Loans, Household Expenses, Large Purchases, Medical/Dental, Motorcycle, RV, Taxes, Vacation, Wedding Loans)
  • LoanOriginalAmount - The origination amount of the loan.
  • BorrowerState - The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.
  • Occupation - The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner - A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.
  • DebtToIncomeRatio - The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).
  • IncomeRange - The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.

The data dictionary describes the other variables in the original dataset not explored in this analysis

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Borrower rate

Distribution of Borrower Rate¶

# histogram

Observation¶

Borrower's rate has a unimodal distribution, with a lot of prosper loans having an interest rate of about 0.32% and the lowest number of loans having interest of 0.04%

Distribution of Loan status¶

In [29]:
# Relative Frequency of the different loan status

# size of figure
plt.figure(figsize = [8,6])

# order of Loan status from bad to good 
status_order = df_relevant['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index

# standard horizontal bar chart
sb.countplot(data = df_relevant, y = 'LoanStatus', color = base_color, order = status_order)

# Returns the sum of all not-null values in the 'LoanStatus' column
n_loan_status = df_relevant['LoanStatus'].value_counts().sum()

# Count the frequency of unique values in the `LoanStatus` column 
# By default, returns the decreasing order of the frequency.
loan_status_counts = df_relevant.LoanStatus.value_counts()


# Logic to print the proportion text on the bars
# use loop to place text one by one
for i in range (loan_status_counts.shape[0]):
    # Remember, `loan_status_counts` contains the frequency of unique values in the `LoanStatus` column in descreasing order
    count = loan_status_counts[i]
    
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into a string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_loan_status)
    
    # Print the string value on the bar
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center', color = 'black')
plt.ylabel('Loan Status')
plt.xlabel('Count');
Observation¶

Over 90% of Prosper loans are in good standing, with 23.2% completely paid off and 66.9% of those loans still being paid off. However, 9.9% of Prosper loans are in bad standing with 6.3% charged off and accounts written off as a loss.

It can be observed that most prosper loans have a Prosper Rating C, and the lowest number of propser loans having a Prosper Rating of AA with the lowest risk

Since there are a lot of categories in the LoanStatus column, especially Past Due having multiple deliquency buckets, the Past Due deliquency buckets will be aggregated as one Past Due category and a column loan_status_aggr created to house the aggregated loan status

In [40]:
# aggregate the multiple `Past Due` deliquency buckets into a single 'Past Due' category
df_relevant['loan_status_aggr'] = df_relevant['LoanStatus'].apply(lambda x: x if 'Past Due' not in x else 'Past Due')

# Convert the "LoanStatus" column from a plain object type into an ordered categorical type
loan_status_group = ['Chargedoff', 'Defaulted', 'Past Due', 'Current', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Completed']
loan_status_order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = loan_status_group)
df_relevant['loan_status_aggr'] = df_relevant['loan_status_aggr'].astype(loan_status_order)

I'll write a function to create three different plots (boxplot, violin plot, and combined box and violin plot). The choice of plots have been assigned to the name of the plot and can be selected as follows;

box_violin_plots(kind, df, x, y, xlabel, ylabel)

Parameters:

kind: the name of the plot you want displayed

  • box --> boxplot
  • violin --> violin plot
  • box_violin --> combined box and violin plot

df: DataFrame, array, or list of arrays, optional

x, y: names of variables in data or vector data

xlabel, ylabel: axis names

The combined box and violin plot is included because box plot only shows summary statistics whereas the violin plot shows the full distribution of the data depicting both summary statistics and the density of each variable. Hence, sometimes the violin plot can be more informative than the boxplot.

In [41]:
# function to display boxplot, violin plot, and a combined box and violin plot
def box_violin_plots(kind, df, x, y, xlabel, ylabel):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    if kind == 'box':
        plt.figure(figsize = [15,7])       
        sb.boxplot(data = df, x = x, y= y, color = base_color)
        plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)
        plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    elif kind == 'violin':
        plt.figure(figsize = [15,7])       
        sb.violinplot(data = df, x = x, y= y, color = base_color)
        plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)
        plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    elif kind == 'box_violin':
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, figsize = [13, 10], sharex= True, sharey = True, constrained_layout = True)
        sb.boxplot(data = df, x = x, y= y, color = base_color, ax = ax[0])
        sb.violinplot(data = df, x = x, y= y, color = base_color, ax = ax[1])
        
        # Use Common Labels for both x and y axis
        ax[0].set_xlabel(""), ax[0].set_ylabel("")
        ax[1].set_xlabel(""), ax[1].set_ylabel("")
        fig.supxlabel(xlabel)
        fig.supylabel(ylabel)
    return
In [42]:

#define boxgrid function
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = base_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# plot   
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_sample, y_vars = ['BorrowerRate'], x_vars = ['IncomeRange','IsBorrowerHomeowner', 'Term'],

plt.show();

It can also be observed that loan term has a positive relationship with Borrower Rate. The 1yr loan term has a significantly lower borrowe rate when compared to a 3yr and 5yr loan term.

Conclusions¶

  • Regardless of an individuals income, borrowers with lower propser score tend to have higher interest rates. So income might only be a determinant in borrowers rate, when there is no obvious difference in prosper score.
  • It can be observed that loans with the same proper ratings usually have a higher borrowers rate as loan term increases. It is evident that loan term is a major determinant of borrower rate, as there is a significant decrease in borrower rate with shorter loan terms
  • For all prosper ratings with the exception of prosper rating A, it can be seen that borrowers that are severely delinquent (chargedoff, defaulted) on loan payments usually have higher borrowers rates.
  • It can also be seen that with the mid-range prosper scores, borrowers that are delinquent (chargedoff, defaulted, Past Due) on loan payments usually have significantly higher borrowers rates than borrowers with the higher prosper scores._
  • When Income is considered, there seems to be minimal difference in borrowers rate for lower interest ratings like HR, E & D. But when observed from the mid prosper rating (C) to the highest prosper rating (AA), there is a significant difference in borrowers rate for unemployed people when compared to employed people.
  • Unlike 2009 and 2010, there seem to be a significant decrease in borrower rate between homeowners and non-homeowners from 2011.
